Knowledge Foundation Belgium.'),(546,183,'time','09:00-09:15'),(547,183,'_edit_last','2'),(548,183,'_edit_lock','1388751138:2'),(549,184,'biography',''),(550,184,'bio',''),(551,184,'description','<p>Hendrik Bogaert and Erwin De Pue will sketch the current status of the implementation of the PSI directive on a federal level. They will lift a corner of the veil of the future and the difficulties of Open Data in Belgium.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Hendrik Bogaert:</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Data have never been so important for public administrations as they are nowadays. It is the government’s task to manage these data, to use them and to make them available for the\r\nbenefit of citizens and companies.</P>\r\n\r\n<p>The Belgian ICT- and e-Government-strategy is based on the “only once”-principle:\r\nadministrations must not ask citizens and companies for information and data that are already available in the organisation. They have access to them through authentic sources. By using these data to the maximum they can deliver faster and more efficient services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These data are also ‘raw material’ for companies that can use them to create new services\r\nand thus stimulate the economy. Often, these new applications also make daily life easier for citizens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The challenge for public administrations is to share the available data through harmonised\r\nlicensing models, to ensure interoperability and to create standard formats.</p>'),(552,184,'time','09:20-10:05'),(553,184,'_edit_last','3'),(554,184,'_edit_lock','1389793100:3'),(555,185,'biography',''),(556,185,'bio',''),(557,185,'description',''),(558,185,'time',''),(559,185,'_edit_last','1'),(560,185,'_edit_lock','1388065899:3'),(561,186,'biography',''),(562,186,'bio',''),(563,186,'description','Erik Mannens will talk about the EWI project. Noël Van Herreweghe will sketch the current status of Open Data in Flanders. He will lift a corner of the veil of the future and the difficulties of Open Data in Flanders. More information about this session TBA. '),(564,186,'time','10:15-10:45'),(565,186,'_edit_last','3'),(566,186,'_edit_lock','1387880853:3'),(567,187,'biography',''),(568,187,'bio',''),(569,187,'description',''),(570,187,'time','10:45-11:15'),(571,187,'_edit_last','1'),(572,187,'_edit_lock','1385595342:1'),(573,188,'biography',''),(574,188,'bio',''),(575,188,'description',''),(576,188,'time',''),(577,188,'_edit_last','1'),(578,188,'_edit_lock','1385595505:1'),(620,197,'biography',''),(621,197,'bio',''),(622,197,'description','Talk with André Blavier from AWT about the state of play and the future of Open Data in Wallonia. More information about this session TBA.'),(623,197,'time','11:35-12:20'),(624,197,'_edit_last','3'),(625,197,'_edit_lock','1388084540:3'),(626,198,'biography',''),(627,198,'bio',''),(628,198,'description','In this session all of the speakers of the break out sessions will give a short pitch on what the attendees can expect from their sessions. In three minutes they will provide the necessary background on their topic and their approach. '),(629,198,'time','12:25-12:55'),(630,198,'_edit_last','3'),(631,198,'_edit_lock','1387881969:3'),(632,199,'biography',''),(633,199,'bio',''),(634,199,'description','The lunch will take place in the Entrance Hall of the beautiful STAM in Ghent. Enjoy the sandwiches, wraps and soup while getting to know your fellow Open Data enthousiasts. \r\n<br></br>\r\n<img alt=\"Entrance hall of STAM Ghent\" src=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Gent_STAM_Onthaal_12-10-2010_10-30-09.JPG/1599px-Gent_STAM_Onthaal_12-10-2010_10-30-09.JPG\" width=\"400\" height=\"266\" />\r\n<br></br>\r\n<a href=\"http://nl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gebruiker:Paul_Hermans/Fotoalbum\" target=\"_blank\">Image by Paul Hermans</a>'),(635,199,'time','13:00-14:00'),(636,199,'_edit_last','3'),(637,199,'_edit_lock','1387882115:3'),(638,200,'biography',''),(639,200,'bio',''),(640,200,'description','<p>The Data Days open-geo-data track will try to address the issue of the sometimes conflicting goals of the OpenStreetMap-community, that uses crowdsourcing as a tool to collect data, and the open-(geo)-data providers/consumers that are also using OpenStreetMap-data.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The questions that we want to answer using a discussion panel are, for example, how to cooperate with the OpenStreetMap-community when you have data that you want on the map? We will try and address the impact on the existing community that large datasets external to OpenStreetMap can have and what about keeping this data up-to-date in OSM? What if you have a specific use-case, how can we work together to improve both our datasets?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some examples are the AGIV CRAB addressing data, De Lijn bustops, URBIS-data in Brussels, specific data for emergency services and the many smaller open-geo-datasets out there.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of this session we hope to walk away with some ideas that can bring together the OpenStreetMap-community and the open-data community to improve the quality and access to some of the open-geo-datasets.</p>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;'),(641,200,'time','14:00-15:30'),(642,200,'_edit_last','3'),(643,200,'_edit_lock','1388752751:3'),(644,201,'biography',''),(645,201,'bio',''),(646,201,'description','Personal urban mobility is changing. Cars are no longer “# 1” anymore, and commuters are less exclusive in the way they move around in their daily life.  Indeed, they use bike-share systems, ride a bus to the train station, or take a taxi back home when working late.  They might also do something entirely different the following day depending on such day’s particular circumstances like weather, traffic, or personal engagements. In this new context, having accurate information and data has become increasingly useful.  Thus, it is good news that as never before, we can now benefit from so many ready-to-use technologies, (smartphones, GPS, mobile Internet, etc.). Major transport companies (national railway, local transport or taxi companies) have begun implementing apps to help people find their way around and to plan the best route possible. However, the best solution is yet to be developed:  one that would meet every single need. Maybe it is not their responsibility anymore because our needs are getting more individual and unique.  Or maybe, simply because the “ultimate” solution will come from the users themselves or from the infinite creativity of the internet business world.'),(647,201,'time','14:00-15:30'),(648,201,'_edit_last','3'),(649,201,'_edit_lock','1389276953:3'),(650,202,'biography',''),(651,202,'bio',''),(652,202,'description','Open Data needs Open Tools in order to be used properly. Irina Bolychevsky, CKAN and Open Government manager will bring you a sessions on how CKAN is such a tool. CKAN is a powerful data management system that makes data accessible – by providing tools to streamline publishing, sharing, finding and using data. CKAN is aimed at data publishers (national and regional governments, companies and organizations) wanting to make their data open and available. Jan Vansteenlandt,  project lead on The Datatank will provide extra information about how The Datatank works very well with CKAN. The DataTank is an open source tool that publishes data from and to the web. It makes your data reusable for data journalists, and developers in a brink of an eye using modern web standards.'),(653,202,'time','14:00-15:30'),(654,202,'_edit_last','3'),(655,202,'_edit_lock','1388746050:3'),(660,204,'biography',''),(661,204,'bio',''),(662,204,'description','<span id=\"docs-internal-guid-16fdc33b-1f95-5b20-a013-c612a37da0bc\"><span style=\"font-size: 15px; font-family: \'Open Sans\'; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Creative Commons and Data. In the vision declaration that has been released by Creative Commons for their ten year anniversary, they have set their mission to nothing less than realizing the full potential of the Internet for driving a new era of development, growth and  productivity. Science, data and open government projects are amongst the top priorities as it becomes evident that these fields will be at the core of the data driven society we are slowly but steadily steering towards. The past two years the Creative Commons community has been working hard on version 4.0 of the licenses, for a great part to enable the data communities around the world , to provide them with suitable tools for opening and reusing data. With their recent release (November 2013) this is a perfect opportunity to take a look at what has changed and why CC is the best option for your open data project.</span></span>'),(663,204,'time',''),(664,204,'_edit_last','3'),(665,204,'_edit_lock','1387804344:3'),(666,205,'biography',''),(667,205,'bio',''),(668,205,'description',''),(669,205,'time','15:30-16:00'),(670,205,'_edit_last','1'),(671,205,'_edit_lock','1385596784:1'),(672,206,'biography',''),(673,206,'bio',''),(674,206,'description','The directive on the re-use of public sector information, so called PSI directive, was changed in June 2013 ( DIRECTIVE 2013/37/EU of the European Parliament and of the Council of 26 June 2013).\r\n\r\nBy 18 July 2015, Member States need to adopt and publish the laws, regulations and administrative provisions necessary to comply with this Directive.\r\n\r\nIn this session you will learn what is at stake at the different Federal and Regional levels: procedure, new points to take into account,…'),(675,206,'time','16:00-17:30'),(676,206,'_edit_last','3'),(677,206,'_edit_lock','1389784868:3'),(678,207,'biography',''),(679,207,'bio',''),(680,207,'description','&nbsp;\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">eGovernment is a strategy to provide administration services online, so-called digital government. Yet; the number of services online is not a measure of success, and the real issue is how to provide better services to citizens. With Open Data as a first step towards more transparency, one can start implementing Open Government strategies to ensure more participation and accessibility for everyone. Open Government is not only about providing more Open Data sets through something like data.gov, it is really about making sure “Government is where people are !”. During this session, we’ll explore some aspects of Open Government and their impact on the democratic processes. We’ll debate also on empowering the administration to use social media tools and connect with external communities gathering citizen-generated information. Recent improvement of the French data.gov, allowing user-generated content to be stored along public data is one example of this social move.</span></p>'),(681,207,'time','16:00-17:30'),(682,207,'_edit_last','3'),(683,207,'_edit_lock','1388065701:3'),(684,208,'biography',''),(685,208,'bio',''),(686,208,'description','<p>Although data journalism is not really new, there is no misunderstanding about the fact that its importance is strongly growing. The promises of new technologies, the continuous availability of enormous sets of data and the size of specialised project teams are bringing IT-driven journalism to the boundaries of the newsroom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During this session about data journalism we will talk about issues and trends within the field. Starting from the story running around the offshore leaks we will handle the different aspects involved in the process. How do we get the data and where do we store it? What kind of tools do newsrooms need to clean, analyse and visualise the data? And when does the journalist comes in? Is he just there to find the story or does he need to develop special skills?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this session different experts from different disciplines will discuss, with the audience, about the difficulties and the trends in data journalism.</p>'),(687,208,'time','16:00-17:30'),(688,208,'_edit_last','3'),(689,208,'_edit_lock','1389009849:3'),(690,209,'biography',''),(691,209,'bio',''),(692,209,'description','Every Open Data enthusiast has a list in their mind of Belgian datasets that they want to see opened up in the near future. In this session, all these lists are going to brainstormed together, and a consolidated list will be published. So bring your own open data wishlist and share what data you want to be open in the foreseeable future. '),(693,209,'time','16:00-17:30'),(694,209,'_edit_last','3'),(695,209,'_edit_lock','1388746446:3'),(700,211,'biography',''),(701,211,'bio',''),(702,211,'description',''),(703,211,'time','17:30-18:00'),(704,211,'_edit_last','1'),(705,211,'_edit_lock','1385597638:1'),(706,212,'biography',''),(707,212,'bio',''),(708,212,'description','Evening programme'),(709,212,'time','18:00-24:00'),(710,212,'_edit_last','1'),(711,212,'_edit_lock','1386237482:2'),(712,213,'biography',''),(713,213,'bio',''),(714,213,'description',''),(715,213,'time',''),(716,213,'_edit_last','2'),(717,213,'_edit_lock','1387276594:2'),(718,215,'biography',''),(719,215,'bio',''),(720,215,'description',''),(721,215,'time',''),(722,215,'_menu_item_type','post_type'),(723,215,'_menu_item_menu_item_parent','0'),(724,215,'_menu_item_object_id','213'),(725,215,'_menu_item_object','page'),(726,215,'_menu_item_target',''),(727,215,'_menu_item_classes','a:1:{i:0;s:0:\"\";}'),(728,215,'_menu_item_xfn',''),(729,215,'_menu_item_url',''),(741,200,'speaker','425;'),(742,209,'speaker','403;'),(784,213,'speaker',''),(785,221,'biography',''),(786,221,'bio',''),(787,221,'description',''),(788,221,'time','10:00-10:30'),(789,221,'speaker',''),(790,221,'_edit_last','2'),(791,221,'_edit_lock','1385719915:2'),(811,225,'biography',''),(812,225,'bio',''),(813,225,'description','<ol>\r\n	<li>Government as Source of Data</li>\r\n	<li>Data Visualization</li>\r\n	<li>Social Media and Open Data</li>\r\n	<li>Public-Private Partnerships in Information Reporting</li>\r\n	<li>Decision Support Models based on Open Data</li>\r\n	<li>Conclusion</li>\r\n	<li>Q&amp;A</li>\r\n</ol>'),(814,225,'time','14:00-15:00'),(815,225,'speaker',''),(816,225,'_edit_lock','1387463783:2'),(817,225,'_edit_last','2'),(824,130,'speaker',''),(831,230,'biography',''),(832,230,'bio',''),(833,230,'description','<p>This session showcases the ENGAGE open data infrastructure (see <a title=\"Engage Data\" href=\"http://www.engagedata.eu\" target=\"_blank\">www.engagedata.eu</a>) by giving a presentation of the project and performing a live demo of the platform. The ENGAGE infrastructure facilitates the publication and use of open data by the public and private sector. ENGAGE is a centralized and collaborative e-Infrastructure providing the necessary tools for dataset processing and acquisition and is differentiated from a simple repository of open public datasets: it is an intelligent social and collaborative space for researchers, data journalists, citizens and other potential end users, who rely on open public data for professional or personal (re-)use. This is polished and ready to be exploited by others in their ventures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MC: Jan Vansteenlandt</p>'),(834,230,'time','15:00-16:00'),(835,230,'speaker','445;'),(836,230,'_edit_last','2'),(837,230,'_edit_lock','1389704370:2'),(838,231,'biography',''),(839,231,'bio',''),(840,231,'description',''),(841,231,'time','10:30-11:00'),(842,231,'speaker',''),(843,231,'_edit_last','2'),(844,231,'_edit_lock','1385724400:2'),(845,232,'biography',''),(846,232,'bio',''),(847,232,'description','The UN e-Government Survey explores the linkages between e-government and sustainable  development efforts.  The Survey looks  at how governments are employing e-government strategies, policies and guidelines on issues such as: whole of government approach, open government, citizen engagement, e-participation, integrated e-services, m-services, open data and social media, and their collective effect on government efficiency and effectiveness.  It also focuses on the relationship between citizen and government, their interactions and how governments are using all aspect of e-government to improve the lives of their citizens.'),(848,232,'time','11:00-12:00'),(849,232,'speaker',''),(850,232,'_edit_last','2'),(851,232,'_edit_lock','1387528700:2'),(852,233,'biography',''),(853,233,'bio',''),(854,233,'description','<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin: 0cm 0cm 10pt;\"><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"mso-ansi-language: EN-US;\"><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri;\">Keynote: Gerald Santucci, Head of Unit \"Knowledge Sharing\" in DG CONNECT - European Commission<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">  </span>“Towards a Joined-up Smart Cities Vision and Strategy for Europe”</span></span></span></span></p>'),(855,233,'time','12:00-13:00'),(856,233,'speaker','259;'),(857,233,'_edit_last','2'),(858,233,'_edit_lock','1387528495:2'),(859,234,'biography',''),(860,234,'bio',''),(861,234,'description',''),(862,234,'time','12:30-14:00'),(863,234,'speaker',''),(864,234,'_edit_lock','1385725800:2'),(865,234,'_edit_last','2'),(866,199,'speaker',''),(867,149,'speaker','330;'),(868,235,'biography',''),(869,235,'bio',''),(870,235,'description',''),(871,235,'time','16:00-16:30'),(872,235,'speaker',''),(873,235,'_edit_last','2'),(874,235,'_edit_lock','1386237208:2'),(875,236,'biography',''),(876,236,'bio',''),(877,236,'description','<ul>\r\n	<li>Part 1 - Status (Noël Van Herreweghe)\r\n2013 has arguably been a really good year for open data at the Flemish government in Belgium, paving the way for even bigger achievements in 2014. Noël Van Herreweghe, the program manager for Open Data, will give us a status, what is still to be done, and the challenges facing this administration.</li>\r\n	<li>Part 2: Technical (Yves Vanderbeken)\r\nIn the second part of this session, Yves Vanderbeken will zoom in on the technical realizations of the Flemish Government to date. He will present an overview of the platform of the Flemish Government, but also focus on the technical architecture and Best Practice scenarios that are being developed to make sure data is correctly extracted, transformed and published on the platform.</li>\r\n</ul>'),(878,236,'time','15:00-16:00'),(879,236,'speaker','330;468;'),(880,236,'_edit_last','2'),(881,236,'_edit_lock','1389703976:2'),(889,236,'_wp_old_slug','citadel-template-applicaties'),(890,238,'biography',''),(891,238,'bio',''),(892,238,'description','Concert - to be confirmed '),(893,238,'time','17:30-24:00'),(894,238,'speaker',''),(895,238,'_edit_last','2'),(896,238,'_edit_lock','1389367725:2'),(897,239,'biography',''),(898,239,'bio',''),(899,239,'description',''),(900,239,'time','09:00-09:30'),(901,239,'speaker',''),(902,239,'_edit_last','1'),(903,239,'_edit_lock','1387875948:3'),(904,240,'biography',''),(905,240,'bio',''),(906,240,'description','<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 6pt; margin-right: 6pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto;\"><i><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"color: #376092; font-size: 10pt;\">Eddy Van der Stock – President of LOLA</span></i></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 6pt; margin-right: 6pt; mso-margin-top-alt: auto; mso-margin-bottom-alt: auto;\"><b><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"color: #376092; font-size: 10pt;\"> </span></b><b><span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"color: #376092; font-size: 10pt;\">Interoperability in practice</span></b></p>'),(907,240,'time','09:30-10:00'),(908,240,'speaker',''),(909,240,'_edit_last','2'),(910,240,'_edit_lock','1388737638:2'),(914,241,'biography',''),(915,241,'bio',''),(916,241,'description','<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <w:WordDocument>\r\n  <w:View>Normal</w:View>\r\n  <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>\r\n  <w:TrackMoves/>\r\n  <w:TrackFormatting/>\r\n  <w:HyphenationZone>21</w:HyphenationZone>\r\n  <w:PunctuationKerning/>\r\n  <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas/>\r\n  <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>\r\n  <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent>\r\n  <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>\r\n